title: First official visit to Europe by SHWF
content_text:
p>The Secretary for Health, Welfare and Food, Dr York Chow, will leave Hong Kong 
on Sunday (May 15) for Geneva, Switzerland, to attend the World Health 
Organisation's 58th World Health Assembly (WHA). He will participate as a member 
of the Chinese delegation.  The World Health Assembly will run from May 16 to 25.  Following his attendance at the WHA meetings, Dr Chow will pay his first 
official visit to Sweden and Belgium.  He will arrive in Stockholm, Sweden on May 18, where he will meet officials from

the Ministry of Health and Social Affairs to establish network with the ministry 
and to learn from the Swedish experience in health and elderly care services 
delivery.  During his stay in Stockholm, he will visit a community-based primary health 
care facility, a group living home for people with dementia diseases and a home 
help service centre for elderly people.  On May 19, Dr Chow will visit a national resource centre on assistive technology 
for people with disabilities.  Dr Chow will then meet with the Swedish Minister for Health and Elderly Care, Ms

Ylva Johansson, to discuss issues on health and elderly care of mutual concern.
 After the meeting, Dr Chow will proceed to Belgium. In the evening, he will 
officiate at the Opening of the Hong Kong Film Night 2005 in Antwerp Film 
Museum. He will have dinner with board members of the Belgium Hong Kong Society 
and other celebrities.  Dr Chow will end his itinerary by visiting the Port of Antwerp on May 20. The 
port is the designated first points of entry of all imports of fruit from

port is the designated first points of entry of all imports of fruit from 
outside the European Union (EU). He will obtain first-hand information on how 
the import of fruit and plants to the EU is being dealt with in the context of 
plant pests and assess their implications for Hong Kong where the existing 
regulatory framework may need to be reviewed.
